<br>
What kind of connection do you have to your ISP? I.e., how is the desktop computer physically connected to the ISP's network? Is it a dial-up account via modem, or an ethernet connection to a cable modem/dsl? Equally important, how does the desktop computer acquire an IP address? Staticly or via DHCP? Will your ISP grant you more than one IP address?<br>
<br>
If you have cable or DSL, chances are that your desktop has an ethernet cable running directly to the &quot;modem&quot; your ISP gave you. If IP addresses are assigned dynamically, and your ISP will let you have more than one IP address (they usually will, but it often costs more), then all you have to do is buy a hub or switch and plug the desktop and the laptop into the switch/hub, and then plug the switch/hub into the cable/dsl box, using the uplink port if possible. You can connect it with one of the regular ports, but it affects which kind of CAT5 cable you need - crossover or straight-through.<br>
<br>
If you have cable or DSL and you either can't get an additional IP address, or you just don't want to pay extra (like me), you'll need to take a different approach. Instead of a hub/switch, you'll need a routher with NAT capabilities, or else you'll need to configure the desktop as a software router with NAT capabilities (using whatever routing software you want - too many to discuss here). There are several cheap NAT routers specifically designed for DSL and cable customers that you can probably just plug-and-go, but NAT configuration and router configuration in general is a bit more complicated, and I don't want to dive into that until you know for sure if you need to do that.<br>
<br>
As for a dial-up connection, you'll need to add an ethernet card to the desktop and the laptop, and then connect them with an cross-over cable, Or connect them both to a hub/switch with straight-through cables. Then you'll need to either configure the desktop as a software router with NATing, or using the &quot;internet connection sharing&quot; thingamajig in Win2K/XP, which is really just configuring the desktop as a NAT router a la Microsoft. Personally I don't trust it, but that doesn't mean it wouldn't work. <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :b --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/tongue.gif ALT=":b"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p><!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>&quot;Really, all of this is just a template that rests atop the basic assumptions this genre has - do things over and over again, until you are strong enough to do them over and over again on a more powerful foe with more powerful abilities. I'm not saying that's good or bad, I'm just putting it out there. The thing that will keep you in this game or any other game of its ilk is the social group that binds you to it. Either that, or OCD.&quot;</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> -- Tycho<br>
